    16777216

    attr/group
  • command.argNames

      (Name: New name for the group. Note that this is an internal name, and should not contain special characters. Message tables should be used for human-readable names.)

      (Fur: Include fur in the baking process)

cmds.batch

(query commandservice cmds.batch ?)

  • command.username
    Batch Commands
  • command.buttonName
    Batch Commands
  • command.desc
    Execute a series of commands. The label is used for the command block wrapping the commands, which in turn are executed in order from c1 to c20, skipping any unset commands. If any of the commands fail, the remaining commands aren't executed.
  • command.usage
    cmds.batch c1:string
  • command.example
    cmds.batch label:{My Batch} c1:{first.Command arg1 arg2} c2:{second.command arg1}
  • command.tooltip
    Execute a series of commands
  • command.icon
    cmds.batch
  • command.flags
    16777216
  • command.category
    cmd
  • command.argNames
    • label: string

      (Label: Label for the command block displayed in the history.)

    • c1: string

      (Command 1: First command to execute.)

    • c2: string

      (Command 2: Second command to execute.)

    • c3: string

      (Command 3: Third command to execute.)

    • c4: string

      (Command 4: Fourth command to execute.)

    • c5: string

      (Command 5: Fifth command to execute.)

    • c6: string

      (Command 6: Sixth command to execute.)

    • c7: string

      (Command 7: Seventh command to execute.)

    • c8: string

      (Command 8: Eighth command to execute.)

    • c9: string

      (Command 9: Ninth command to execute.)

    • c10: string

      (Command 10: Tenth command to execute.)

    • c11: string

      (Command 11: Eleventh command to execute.)

    • c12: string

      (Command 12: Twelfth command to execute.)

    • c13: string

      (Command 13: Thirteenth command to execute.)

    • c14: string

      (Command 14: Fourteenth command to execute.)

    • c15: string

      (Command 15: Fifteenth command to execute.)

    • c16: string

      (Command 16: Sixteenth command to execute.)

    • c17: string

      (Command 17: Seventeenth command to execute.)

    • c18: string

      (Command 18: Eighteenth command to execute.)

    • c19: string

      (Command 19: Nineteenth command to execute.)

    • c20: string

      (Command 20: Twentieth command to execute.)

    cmds.fireAgain
  • command.icon
    cmds.fireAgain
  • command.flags
    16778240
  • command.category
    cmd
  • command.argNames

      (Mode: Which recently fired command to re-execute. If omitted, the most recently executed form or key command will be fired.)

      (Mode: True to allow selection commands to be re-executed. Defaults to true.)

    • raw: boolean

      (Raw: True to execute a command exactly how it was executed by the form, key or mouse butotn. If false, the command is executed after any command dialogs were filled in or argument parsing has occurred. Defaults to true.)

  • command.buttonName

    cmd/script/dialog

      (Format: Internal name for the format. This is returned for the format selected by the user by querying dialog.saveFileFormat.)

    • username: string

      (Username: Name displayed in the file dialog.)

    • loadPattern: string

      (Load Pattern: A semicolon-delimited list of extensions supported by this format, used to filter open dialogs. Each extension should included a leading asterisk and period for proper filtering.)

    • saveExtension: string

      (Save Extension: The default extension, which will automatically be appended to the end of the path entered into the save dialog. This should not include a leading period.)

dircache.copy

(query commandservice dircache.copy ?)

  • command.username
    Copy File
  • command.desc
    Copy a file and all associated cache and markup files. If overwrite is false and the file already exists, a new file will be created with a unique filename. Copying directories is not supported.
  • command.usage
    dircache.copy source:filepath dest:filepath overwrite:boolean
  • command.icon
    dircache.copy
  • command.argNames
    • source: filepath

      (Source: Full local path to the source file to copy.)

    • dest: filepath

      (Destination: Full local path of the new filename for the copy. This is expected to include the name of the file itself, not just the path to the destination folder.)

    • overwrite: boolean

      (Overwrite: If true, and if a file already exists at the the destination, the file will be overwritten. If it already exists and this is set to false, the copyied file will be given a unique name.)

  • command.username
    Apply Dynamic Impulses
  • command.desc
    Sets random impulse values to the selected dynamic items
  • command.usage
    dynamics.rigid.applyImpulses
  • command.icon
    dynamics.rigid.applyImpulses
  • command.flags
    100663296
  • command.argNames
    • impulseX: force

      (Impulse On X: The force be applied on the objects local X axis)

    • impulseXVar: force

      (Impulse X +/-: Add randomness to the X arguement. This is per-item)

    • impulseY: force

      (Impulse On Y: The force be applied on the objects local Y axis)

    • impulseYVar: force

      (Impulse Y +/-: Add randomness to the Y arguement. This is per-item)

    • impulseZ: force

      (Impulse On Z: The force be applied on the objects local Z axis)

    • impulseZVar: force

      (Impulse Z +/-: Add randomness to the Z arguement. This is per-item)

    • impulsePosX: distance

      (Impulse Postion On X: The position, in local space, to apply the impulse from. This will cause the object to spin as the force will be applied off center)

    • impulsePosXVar: distance

      (Position X +/-: Add randomness to the X position arguement. This is per-item)

    • impulsePosY: distance

      (Impulse Postion On Y: The position, in local space, to apply the impulse from. This will cause the object to spin as the force will be applied off center)

    • impulsePosYVar: distance

      (Position Y +/-: Add randomness to the X position arguement. This is per-item)

    • impulsePosZ: distance

      (Impulse Postion On Z: The position, in local space, to apply the impulse from. This will cause the object to spin as the force will be applied off center)

    • impulsePosZVar: distance

      (Position Z +/-: Add randomness to the X position arguement. This is per-item)

    • impulseTorqueX: force

      (Impulse Torque On X: The position, in local space, the axis to apply the impulse around. This will cause the item to rotate around the X axis)

    • impulseTorqueXVar: force

      (Torque X +/-: Add randomness to the X torque arguement. This is per-item)

    • impulseTorqueY: force

      (Impulse Torque On Y: The position, in local space, the axis to apply the impulse around. This will cause the item to rotate around the Y axis)

    • impulseTorqueYVar: force

      (Torque Y +/-: Add randomness to the Y torque arguement. This is per-item)

    • impulseTorqueZ: force

      (Impulse Torque On Z: The position, in local space, the axis to apply the impulse around. This will cause the item to rotate around the Z axis)

    • impulseTorqueZVar: force

      (Torque Z +/-: Add randomness to the Z torque arguement. This is per-item)

file.gridInsert

(query commandservice file.gridInsert ?)

  • command.username
    Insert Grid Rows/Columns
  • command.desc
    Insert rows or columns into a Grid style Preset Browser.
  • command.usage
    file.gridInsert asRow:boolean count:integer before:boolean
  • command.icon
    file.gridInsert
  • command.category
    file
  • command.argNames
    • asRow: boolean

      (As Row: If true, this adds new rows; if false, it adds new columns.)

    • count: integer

      (Count: The number of new rows or columns to add.)

    • before: boolean

      (Before: If true, the new rows/columns are inserted before the target position; if false, they are inserted after.)

    • dir: filepath

      (Directory: The diectory into which the rows/columns are added. If not set, the first selected filepath is used.)

    • pos: integer

      (Position: The grid position within the directory to insert the rows/columns. This is only used if "dir" is set; otherwise, the position is obtained from the first selected filepath.)

file.gridRemove

(query commandservice file.gridRemove ?)

  • command.username
    Remove Grid Rows/Columns
  • command.desc
    Remove rows or columns from a Grid style Preset Browser. This only removes empty space; the files themselves are not affected.
  • command.usage
    file.gridRemove asRow:boolean count:integer
  • command.icon
    file.gridRemove
  • command.category
    file
  • command.argNames
    • asRow: boolean

      (As Row: If true, this removes rows; if false, it removes columns.)

    • count: integer

      (Count: The number of rows or columns to remove.)

    • dir: filepath

      (Directory: The diectory from which the rows/columns are removed. If not set, the first selected filepath is used.)

    • pos: integer

      (Position: The grid position within the directory to remove the rows/columns. This is only used if "dir" is set; otherwise, the position is obtained from the first selected filepath.)

    • onlyIfEmpty: boolean

      (Only If Empty: If true, rows/columns are removed only if they are completely empty; if false, the rows/columns empty cells in the rows/columns are removed even if there are other files in those rows/columns.)

layout.create

(query commandservice layout.create ?)

  • command.username
    Create Layout
  • command.buttonName
    Create Layout
  • command.desc
    Create a new layout.
  • command.usage
    layout.create ?
  • command.tooltip
    Create Layout
  • command.icon
    layout.create
  • command.flags
    16777216
  • command.category
    viewport/layout
  • command.argNames
    • title: string

      (Title: Layout title.)

    • x: integer

      (X: Horizontal position of the layout's window.)

    • y: integer

      (Y: Vertical position of the layout's window.)

    • width: integer

      (Width: Width of the layout's window.)

    • height: integer

      (Height: Height of the layout's window.)

    • minSizeX: integer

      (Minimum Size X: Minimum width of the layout's window.)

    • minSizeY: integer

      (Minimum Size Y: Minimum height of the layout's window.)

    • maxSizeX: integer

      (Maximum Size X: Maximum width of the layout's window.)

    • maxSizeY: integer

      (Maximum Size Y: Maximum height of the layout's window.)

    • persistent: boolean

      (Persistent: Toggles peristent state.)

    • maximize: integer

      (Maximize: If set, the window will open maximized.)

    • style: integer

      (Style: Window style, either "standard", "palette", "popoverClickOff" or "popoverRollOff". Palettes all be hidden or shown using layout.togglePalettes.)

    • command: string

      (Command: If set, this command will be executed every time the layout is restored.)

    • icon: string

      (Icon: If set, this icon will be drawn on the button of layout.restore and layout.createOrClose.)

    • opaque: boolean
    • class: string

      (Switcher Class: Determines which set of layouts can be switched in this window through the Layout Switcher. If unset, this defaults to the "normal" class.)

    • pointAt: string

      (Point At: When combined with the popoverPointAt style, this creats a popover that points at the region specified. The argument is expected to be formated as "x1 y1 x2 y2 sides", where "sides", if present, indicates that the popover should be placed to the side of the region instead of above/below it if possible.)

    • layout: string

      (Layout: Name of the layout to restore into the newly created window.)

layout.createOrClose

(query commandservice layout.createOrClose ?)

  • command.username
    Create or Close Layout
  • command.buttonName
    Create/Close Layout
  • command.desc
    Create a new layout, or close an existing layout with the same cookie.
  • command.usage
    layout.createOrClose cookie:string ? ?
  • command.tooltip
    Create or Close Layout
  • command.icon
    layout.createOrClose
  • command.flags
    16777216
  • command.category
    viewport/layout
  • command.argNames
    • cookie: string

      (Cookie: A cookie identifying this window. If a window with this cookie is already opened, it will be closed; otherwise, a new layout will be created using the remaining arguments.)

    • layout: string

      (Layout: Name of the layout to restore into the newly created window.)

    • open: boolean

      (Open: Can be used to force a layout to open or close, but is most useful when queried and inserted into a form, thus allowing it to create a checkbox-style control.)

    • title: string

      (Title: Layout title.)

    • x: integer

      (X: Horizontal position of the layout's window.)

    • y: integer

      (Y: Vertical position of the layout's window.)

    • width: integer

      (Width: Width of the layout's window.)

    • height: integer

      (Height: Height of the layout's window.)

    • minSizeX: integer

      (Minimum Size X: Minimum width of the layout's window.)

    • minSizeY: integer

      (Minimum Size Y: Minimum height of the layout's window.)

    • maxSizeX: integer

      (Maximum Size X: Maximum width of the layout's window.)

    • maxSizeY: integer

      (Maximum Size Y: Maximum height of the layout's window.)

    • persistent: boolean

      (Persistent: Toggles peristent state.)

    • maximize: integer

      (Maximize: If set, the window will open maximized.)

    • style: integer

      (Style: Window style, either "standard", "palette", "popoverClickOff" or "popoverRollOff". Palettes all be hidden or shown using layout.togglePalettes.)

    • command: string

      (Command: If set, this command will be executed every time the layout is restored.)

    • icon: string

      (Icon: If set, this icon will be drawn on the button of layout.restore and layout.createOrClose.)

    • opaque: boolean

      (Opaque: Can be used to force a normally transparent window (like a popover) to be opaque)

    • class: string

      (Switcher Class: Determines which set of layouts can be switched in this window through the Layout Switcher. If unset, this defaults to the "normal" class.)

    • pointAt: string

      (Point At: When combined with the popoverPointAt style, this creats a popover that points at the region specified. The argument is expected to be formated as "x1 y1 x2 y2 sides", where "sides", if present, indicates that the popover should be placed to the side of the region instead of above/below it if possible.)

loaderOptions.PowerTranslators

(query commandservice loaderOptions.PowerTranslators ?)

  • command.username
    Power Translators CAD File Loader Options
  • command.usage
    loaderOptions.PowerTranslators #filename:string ?output_item_type:{cadio_output_item_MESH|cadio_output_item_CAD|cadio_output_item_STATIC_MESH} ?instance_mode:{cadio_instances_COPY|cadio_instances_INSTANCE|cadio_instances_REPLICATOR} ?tessellation_override:{cadio_tessellation_override_COURSE|cadio_tessellation_override_MEDIUM|cadio_tessellation_override_FINE|cadio_tessellation_override_VERY_FINE|cadio_tessellation_override_SUPER_FINE|cadio_tessellation_override_NONE} ?tess_angle:angle ?use_bbox_rel_attr:boolean ?tess_dist:distance ?min_facet_width:distance ?max_facet_width:distance ?tess_dist_bboxrel:percent ?min_facet_width_bboxrel:percent ?max_facet_width_bboxrel:percent ?cadio_up_axis:axis ?cadio_bbox_size:distance ?cadio_rest_on_ground:boolean ?cadio_use_proxy:boolean ?cadio_import_materials:boolean
  • command.icon
    loaderOptions.PowerTranslators
  • command.flags
    16777216
  • command.argNames
    • filename: string

      (CAD File: File to load.)

    • output_item_type: integer

      (Output Item: Generate static Mesh items, standard Mesh items, or CAD items.)

    • instance_mode: integer

      (Duplicates: Load duplicate items as Copies, Instances, or Replicators.)

    • tessellation_override: integer

      (Mesh Quality Presets: Override Mesh Creation Quality Settings.)

    • tess_angle: angle

      (Angle: Maximum angle between tessellated polygons.)

    • use_bbox_rel_attr: boolean

      (Bounding Box Relative: Set parameters relative to the bounding box of the CAD model.)

    • tess_dist: distance

      (Distance Tolerance: Define the maximum distance between the tessellated and CAD surfaces.)

    • min_facet_width: distance

      (Minimum Edge: Set the minimum edge length.)

    • max_facet_width: distance

      (Maximum Edge: Set the maximum edge length.)

    • tess_dist_bboxrel: percent

      (Distance Tolerance (%): Define the maximum distance between the tessellated and CAD surfaces (as a percentage of the global bounding box).)

    • min_facet_width_bboxrel: percent

      (Minimum Edge (%): Set the minimum Edge Length(as a percentage of the global bounding box).)

    • max_facet_width_bboxrel: percent

      (Maximum Edge (%): Set the maximum Edge Length (as a percentage of the global bounding box).)

    • cadio_up_axis: axis

      (Up Axis: The axis from the CAD model that should be mapped to the vertical axis in modo.)

    • cadio_bbox_size: distance

      (User Bounding Box Size: This option will resize the default bounding box based on the value provided.)

    • cadio_rest_on_ground: boolean

      (Rest on Ground: When checked, this option will cause the imported file to rest on the ground plane.)

    • cadio_use_proxy: boolean

      (Use Proxy: Will use previously generated IwProd proxy file to allow for faster reloading of IGES and STEP files.)

    • cadio_import_materials: boolean

      (Import Materials: If toggled ON, create materials from material information found in CAD files.)

mesh.shatter.cluster

(query commandservice mesh.shatter.cluster ?)

  • command.username
    Shatter Cluster
  • command.desc
    desc
  • command.usage
    mesh.shatter.cluster numPieces:integer numSecondaryPieces:integer
  • command.icon
    mesh.shatter.cluster;mesh.shatter
  • command.flags
    100663296
  • command.argNames
    • centerToBounds: boolean

      (Center to Bounds: After the shatter, the item center will be moved to the center of the shards bounding box)

    • hideSource: boolean

      (Hide Source: After shatter, the source item will be hidden)

    • addToGroup: boolean

      (Add to Group: After shatter, will group the shards to a group locator)

    • cuttingMaterial: string

      (Cutting Material: This is the material that will be applied to the inside, cut surfaces. It a preexisting material exists with this name, it will be applied, otherwise a new material is created. This new material has no smoothing so to better emulate a cut surface)

    • randomSeed: integer

      (Random Seed: Change the random number generator used for creating the shards)

    • genNormalMap: boolean

      (Generate Normal Map: Will create a normal vmap for the shards. This keeps the normals from the source item so that you would see smoothing between the original surface and the cut surface)

    • numPieces: integer

      (Number of Pieces: The maximum number of pieces this object will be cut into. Since this is the number of pieces the items bounding box is cut into, the number of actual pieces created could be less)

    • numSecondaryPieces: integer

      (Secondary Pieces: The number of additional shards created around each of the primary pieces)

    • randomDistancePercent: percent

      (Random Distance %: This is the distance the secondary shards will be created from the primary pieces. This is the percentage relative to the size of the mesh item.)

    • randomDistance: distance

      (Random Distance: This is the distance the secondary shards will be created from the primary pieces. This is an absolute world value.)

mesh.shatter.radial

(query commandservice mesh.shatter.radial ?)

  • command.username
    Shatter Radial
  • command.desc
    Shatters in a radial pattern like a rock going through a piece of glass. The meshes pivot is used as the center of this shatter
  • command.usage
    mesh.shatter.radial radialRays:integer radialRings:integer
  • command.icon
    mesh.shatter.radial;mesh.shatter
  • command.flags
    100663296
  • command.argNames
    • centerToBounds: boolean

      (Center to Bounds: After the shatter, the item center will be moved to the center of the shards bounding box)

    • hideSource: boolean

      (Hide Source: After shatter, the source item will be hidden)

    • addToGroup: boolean

      (Add to Group: After shatter, will group the shards to a group locator)

    • cuttingMaterial: string

      (Cutting Material: This is the material that will be applied to the inside, cut surfaces. It a preexisting material exists with this name, it will be applied, otherwise a new material is created. This new material has no smoothing so to better emulate a cut surface)

    • randomSeed: integer

      (Random Seed: Change the random number generator used for creating the shards)

    • genNormalMap: boolean

      (Generate Normal Map: Will create a normal vmap for the shards. This keeps the normals from the source item so that you would see smoothing between the original surface and the cut surface)

    • radialRays: integer

      (Radial Rays: The number of sections going out from the center of this shatter)

    • radialRings: integer

      (Radial Rings: The number of sections going around the center of this shatter)

    • radialRotate: angle

      (Radial Rotation: The amount each ring is rotated from the one before it)

    • radialRadius: percent

      (Radial Radius: This is the distance the outer ring will be created from the center. This is the percentage relative to the size of the mesh item.)

    • randomDistancePercent: percent

      (Random Distance %: This is the maximum distance each shard will be moved from the location it was initially created. This is the percentage relative to the size of the mesh item.)

    • randomDistance: distance

      (Random Distance: This is the maximum distance each shard will be moved from the location it was initially created. This is an absolute world value.)

    • axis: axis

      (Axis: The "Up" direction from which the shatter rays eminate)

  • command.username
    Scene Tag
  • command.buttonName
    Scene Tag
  • command.desc
    Edit a tag of the current scene.
  • command.usage
    scene.tag mode:{number|string} ?tag:* ?value:string
  • command.example
    scene.tag number 2 "Tag Value"
  • command.tooltip
    Scene Tag
  • command.icon
    scene.tag
  • command.flags
    100663296
  • command.category
    item/tag
  • command.argNames
    • mode: integer

      (Mode: Specify the tag by number of by string.)

    • tag:

      (Tag: Tag to affect the value of.)

    • value: string

      (Value: String to assign to the tag.)

scene.tagAdd

(query commandservice scene.tagAdd ?)

  • command.username
    Add Scene Tags
  • command.buttonName
    Add Tags
  • command.desc
    Add one or more scene tags to a scene.
  • command.usage
    scene.tagAdd taglist:string
  • command.example
    scene.tagAdd TAG1;TAG2;TAG3
  • command.tooltip
    Add scene tags
  • command.icon
    scene.tagAdd
  • command.flags
    100663296
  • command.category
    item/tag
  • command.argNames
    • taglist: string

      (Tag List: A semicolon-delimited list of four-character tags.)

  • command.tooltip
    Add a channel to the Schematic
  • command.icon
    schematic.addChannel
  • command.flags
    100663296
  • command.category
    schematic
  • command.argNames
    • channel: &channel

      (Channel: The channel to add.)

    • group: &item

      (Group: The assembly group to which the channel is added.)

    • item: &item

      (Item: The optional node item to which the channel will be attached.)

      (X Position: The x position of the channel in the Schematic.)

    • posY: float

      (Y Position: The y position of the channel in the Schematic.)

    • chanIdx: string
    • show: integer
    • vector: integer

select.typeFrom

(query commandservice select.typeFrom ?)

  • command.username
    Select Type from List
  • command.desc
    Test to see if the first of a list of types is currently active. Useful for creating selection mode toggle buttons.
  • command.usage
    select.typeFrom typelist:string ?
  • command.example
    select.typeFrom "vertex;edge;polygon;item" 1
  • command.help
    command:select.typeFrom
  • command.icon
    select.typeFrom
  • command.flags
    100671616
  • command.toggleArg
    1
  • command.category
    select
  • command.argNames
    • typelist: string

      (Type List: Semicolon-delimited list of types. The first of these is the type toggled by the enable argument, while the reast are tested to see if they were more recently made the current selection type.)

    • enable: boolean

      (Enable: Returns 1 if the first type in the list is current, and 0 if not. Set to 1 to create a toggle button that turns the first type in the list on and off, as well as turning off when another selection mode from the list is selected.)

    sun.color ? ? ? ?
  • command.icon
    sun.color
  • command.flags
    16777216
  • command.category
    item/light
  • command.argNames
    • longitude: angle

      (Longitude: North longitude)

    • latitude: angle

      (Latitude: West latitude)

    • day: integer

      (Day: Day of month)

    • month: integer

      (Month: Month of year)

    • year: integer

      (Year: Four-digit year, common era)

    • timezone: float

      (Time Zone: Counting from Greenwich (=0), west is negative.)

    • time: timeofday

      (Time: Time of day)

    • haze: float

      (Haze: Atmospheric Turbidity)

    • gamma: float

      (Gamma: Gamma correction level for solar color)

    • color: color

      (Color: Normalized solar color. Query this)

    • power: float

      (Power: Solar irradiance (W/m^2). Query this)

    • azimuth: angle

      (Azimuth: Solar Azimuth angle from North. Query this)

    • elevation: angle

      (Elevation: Solar Elevation angle. Query this)

(query commandservice telnet.listen ?)

  • command.username
    Telnet Listen
  • command.desc
    Start or stop the telnet server.
  • command.usage
    telnet.listen ?
  • command.icon
    telnet.listen
  • command.category
    network/telnet
  • command.argNames
    • port: integer

      (Port: The port to start listening on for incoming connections.)

    • raw: boolean

      (Raw: If true, telnet communication uses raw NUL-terminated ASCII strings for communication, which is useful for inter-process communication. If false (default), it uses the telnet protocol, which is useful when connecting with a true telnet client.)

    • open: boolean

      (Open: If true (default), the server starts listening on the port in the given mode. If false, the server stops listening, although any connections will remain open.)
